  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Real estate agent commissions in Queensland are not regulated or fixed by law. There is no government-set rate, no industry floor, and no ceiling. Every commission is negotiated between the agent and the vendor before the agency agreement is signed. That agreement, the Form 6, is a legally binding contract, and the commission terms are part of it. Once you sign, the agreed rate applies unless both parties agree to amend it.</p>

      <p>This means commission is, in principle, always negotiable. But whether negotiating it down is actually in your interest is a different question to whether you legally can.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What commission rates look like in Brisbane's inner east in 2026</h2>
      <p>Commission structures in Brisbane generally take one of two forms: a percentage of the sale price, or a flat fee. Percentage rates for residential property in Brisbane's inner-east suburbs typically sit between 2% and 2.75% of the sale price, with most full-service agents operating somewhere in that range. Some agencies use a tiered structure where a lower percentage applies up to a price threshold and a higher rate applies above it, which is designed to incentivise the agent to push for a higher result.</p>

      <p>Flat-fee models are also available, often from discount agencies or online-only services. These typically charge between $5,000 and $15,000 regardless of the sale price. For properties in the $600,000 to $800,000 range that is broadly comparable to a percentage-based commission. For properties above $1 million, a flat fee can appear significantly cheaper on paper.</p>

      <p>What is rarely disclosed upfront is that marketing costs are almost always separate. Whether you pay a percentage or a flat fee, expect to budget an additional $3,000 to $8,000 for a professional marketing campaign in this market, covering photography, videography, floor plan, digital advertising, signage, and print. Some agents bundle this into their offer; most do not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What justifies a higher commission rate</h2>
      <p>An agent asking 2.5% is not simply charging more than one asking 2%. They may be offering a materially different service: more active buyer management, stronger negotiation experience, a genuine database of qualified buyers in your suburb, proven auction outcomes, or a track record of achieving results above the suburb median. None of those things are guaranteed by a higher commission, but a lower commission almost never buys you more of them.</p>

      <p>The leverage an agent brings to a negotiation on your behalf is worth considerably more than the difference between commission rates. On a $1.2 million property, the difference between a 2% and a 2.5% commission is $6,000. A skilled negotiator who extracts an extra $20,000 from a motivated buyer has more than paid for that difference. An agent who accepts the first offer to close the file quickly has cost you far more.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why the cheapest agent is not always the best choice</h2>
      <p>The incentive problem with commission is simple: a lower rate means the agent receives less for every dollar they achieve above your reserve or asking price. On a $1 million property at 2% commission, a $20,000 improvement in the sale price earns the agent an extra $400. For that same agent, moving to the next listing is often more financially rational than spending three additional days managing a negotiation to extract that $20,000 for you.</p>

      <p>This does not mean all low-commission agents are disengaged. But it does mean the incentive structure matters, and you should be satisfied that the agent you choose has a genuine motivation to maximise your result, not just to close the transaction. Ask directly: how do you handle multiple offers? What is your approach when a buyer comes in at your reserve? Have you achieved results materially above the listed price for comparable properties recently?</p>

      <p>Discount agencies and flat-fee models work best for vendors who are comfortable managing significant parts of the process themselves, for properties in very strong demand where buyers will come regardless of how actively the agent works the campaign, or for investment sales where the vendor has done this before and knows exactly what they want. For a family home in Camp Hill, Morningside, or Bulimba that represents your largest financial transaction, the $3,000 you might save on commission is a poor trade for reduced negotiation pressure on the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to compare agents on value rather than rate</h2>
      <p>Before you discuss commission with any agent, ask for their recent results in your suburb and price range. Specifically: comparable sales in the past 12 months, the list price versus the achieved price for each, and days on market. This is verifiable information you can cross-check on property data platforms. An agent who consistently achieves above the median for comparable properties is demonstrably worth more than one who does not, regardless of what either charges.</p>

      <p>Also ask about their negotiation process. How do they handle a buyer who offers at the floor on day one? Do they call every buyer on their database before going to market? What happens if the first open home produces no strong leads? These process questions reveal whether the agent manages campaigns actively or passively, and that distinction has a far larger impact on your result than whether you agreed on 2% or 2.2%.</p>

      <p>When you do negotiate the commission itself, the more productive approach is to ask what is included at their standard rate, what they would do additionally at a higher rate, and whether they offer any performance-linked structure. A tiered commission where the rate increases above a certain price threshold aligns the agent's incentive directly with your outcome, which is generally a better arrangement for both parties than simply pressing for a lower flat rate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to ask before signing a Form 6</h2>
      <p>The Form 6 is the formal authority you give an agent to sell your property. Before you sign, make sure you understand the following: the commission rate and how it is calculated, whether marketing costs are included or separate, the term of the agreement (typically 60 to 90 days for residential property), the termination conditions if you are unhappy with performance, and whether the agreement is exclusive or conjunctional. An exclusive agreement means only that agent can sell the property during the term. A conjunctional arrangement allows other agents to bring buyers, with the commission split between them.</p>

      <p>Read the Form 6 carefully before signing. If an agent is reluctant to explain any clause or presses you to sign quickly, that is worth noting. The agreement protects both parties, and a transparent agent will take the time to walk through it with you.</p>

